										<footer class="article-contributor contributors">
									

<div class="block-contributor">
		

		<div class="block-contributor-content">
		<div class="block-contributor-bio small">
			<p><strong><span class="smallcaps">Connie May Fowler</span></strong> lives on a small Mexican island in the Caribbean, where she makes a mean mole sauce, has grown to hate cruise-ship tourists, and can say, “Please get out of my yard,” in Mayan. Her essay in this issue is from her forthcoming memoir, <em>A Million Fragile Bones</em>, about living through the BP Deepwater Horizon oil disaster. It will be published in April by Twisted Road Publications.</p><a href="/contributors/connie-may-fowler" class="block-contributor-link link-alt small">More From This Contributor&nbsp;▸</a>		</div>
	</div>
</div>

